#: src/index.md:3
msgid "Welcome to the Chester Programming Language documentation."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:5
msgid "This book is divided into two sections:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:6
msgid ""
"**[Guide](guide/universal-syntax.md)**: A high-level explanation of the "
"concepts and design decisions."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:7
msgid ""
"**[Reference](references/syntax-spec.md)**: Technical specifications and "
"grammar details."
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:3
msgid ""
"Chester utilizes a **Universal Parsed Syntax** represented by a generic "
"Concrete Syntax Tree (CST). Unlike traditional compilers where the parser "
"must be aware of language-specific constructs (such as variable "
"declarations, class definitions, or control flow), Chester's parsing phase "
"is completely agnostic of these details."
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:5
msgid ""
"This design enables a flexible, robust, and tooling-friendly front-end that "
"can adapt to changing language features or even serve as a base for "
"completely different programming languages without modifying the tokenizer "
"or parser."
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:9
msgid "Design Benefits"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:11
msgid "1. Zero Language-Specific Keywords"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:12
msgid ""
"The parser and tokenizer do not have hardcoded keywords like `if`, `while`, "
"`def`, `class`, or `import`. The parser simply parses these words as generic "
"`Symbol` nodes. For example, the statement:"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:14
msgid ""
"```\n"
"def main(): Unit = { println(\"hello\") }\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:17
msgid "is parsed into a `SeqOf` containing:"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:18
msgid "`Symbol(\"def\")`"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:19
msgid "`Symbol(\"main\")`"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:20
msgid "`Tuple(...)`"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:21
msgid "`Symbol(\":\")`"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:22
msgid "`Symbol(\"Unit\")`"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:23
msgid "`Symbol(\"=\")`"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:24
msgid "`Block(...)`"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:26
msgid "2. De-coupled Elaboration Phase"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:27
msgid ""
"Because parsing produces a generic tree of symbols and delimiters, the "
"language's actual grammar rules and semantics are deferred to the "
"**Elaboration** phase. During elaboration:"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:28
msgid "The CST is validated and compiled into an **Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)**."
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:29
msgid ""
"If we want to change how functions are defined or add a new control flow "
"keyword, we only need to update the Elaborator. The core parser remains "
"untouched."
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:31
msgid "3. High Tolerance for Incomplete Code (IDE Friendly)"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:32
msgid ""
"IDE tools require syntax trees for code that is currently being typed (and "
"is therefore syntactically invalid). Because the universal parser only "
"enforces matching delimiters (`()`, `[]`, `{}`), it can recover from errors "
"extremely gracefully. For example, if a user writes:"
msgstr ""

#: src/guide/universal-syntax.md:40
msgid ""
"The parser easily detects the missing parenthesis, records the error, "
"recovers immediately at the semicolon/newline, and parses `b` as a "
"subsequent statement in the block. This makes building language servers "
"(LSP) and syntax highlighting tools straightforward."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:1
msgid "Universal Parsed Syntax Specification"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:3
msgid ""
"This document defines the formal lexical and syntactic grammar of the "
"Chester universal parsed syntax."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:7
msgid "Lexical Grammar"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:9
msgid "1. Characters and Code Points"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:10
msgid ""
"All input is treated as a sequence of Unicode code points. Unicode emojis "
"and private-use characters are fully supported as part of identifier naming "
"rules."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:12
msgid "2. Whitespace and Comments"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:13
msgid ""
"**Whitespace**: Any sequence of characters matching "
"`java.lang.Character.isWhitespace`. Line breaks (`\\n"
"`, `\\r`) are recorded inside whitespace tokens."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:14
msgid ""
"**Line Comment**: Starts with `//` and consumes characters until a line "
"break (`\\n"
"`, `\\r`) or EOF."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:15
msgid ""
"**Block Comment**: Starts with `/*` and ends with `*/`. Block comments "
"support arbitrary nesting (e.g., `/* outer /* inner */ outer */`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:17
msgid "3. Literals"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:18
msgid "**StringLiteral**: Double-quoted text. Escape sequences supported:"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:19
msgid "`\\n` (newline)"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:20
msgid "`\\t` (horizontal tab)"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:21
msgid "`\\r` (carriage return)"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:22
msgid "`\\\\` (backslash)"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:23
msgid "`\\\"` (double quote)"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:24
msgid ""
"Any other escape sequence `\\<char>` triggers a tokenization error but falls "
"back to the literal character `<char>`."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:25
msgid ""
"**IntegerLiteral**: Consists of digits `[0-9]` optionally separated by "
"underscores `_` (which are ignored during parsing)."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:26
msgid ""
"**RationalLiteral**: Consists of an integer literal, followed directly by "
"`/`, followed directly by another integer literal."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:27
msgid ""
"**SymbolLiteral**: Starts with a single quote `'` followed directly by "
"identifier characters (e.g., `'foo`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:29
msgid "4. Identifiers and Operators"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:30
msgid "**Identifier**:"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:31
msgid "Starts with a letter (`isLetter`), emoji (`codePointIsEmoji`), or `_`."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:32
msgid "Can contain letters, emojis, digits, `_`, or `-` (middle wording symbol)."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:33
msgid "Must end with a letter, emoji, digit, or `_`."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:34
msgid "**OperatorIdentifier**:"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:35
msgid ""
"Consists entirely of one or more operator characters from the set: "
"`.:=-+\\|<>/?`~!@$%^&\\*\\`."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:39
msgid "Syntactic Grammar (CST)"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:41
msgid "The Concrete Syntax Tree (CST) parses tokens into structural forms:"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:43
msgid "EBNF Grammar"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:45
msgid ""
"```ebnf\n"
"File            ::= BlockBody EOF\n"
"BlockBody       ::= ( Statement \";\" )* Expression?\n"
"Statement       ::= SeqOf\n"
"Expression      ::= SeqOf\n"
"\n"
"SeqOf           ::= Atom+\n"
"Atom            ::= Symbol\n"
"                  | StringLiteral\n"
"                  | IntegerLiteral\n"
"                  | SymbolLiteral\n"
"                  | Tuple\n"
"                  | ListLiteral\n"
"                  | Block\n"
"                  | Comment\n"
"\n"
"Symbol          ::= Identifier | OperatorIdentifier | \".\"\n"
"\n"
"Tuple           ::= \"(\" DelimitedBody \")\"\n"
"ListLiteral     ::= \"[\" DelimitedBody \"]\"\n"
"DelimitedBody   ::= ( SeqOf \",\" )* SeqOf? \",\"?\n"
"\n"
"Block           ::= \"{\" BlockBody \"}\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:70
msgid "CST Mappings"
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:71
msgid "**`Symbol`**: Any identifier, operator, or single dot `.`."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:72
msgid ""
"**`Tuple`**: Parentheses enclosing a comma-separated list of elements. "
"Trailing commas are permitted."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:73
msgid ""
"**`ListLiteral`**: Square brackets enclosing a comma-separated list of "
"elements. Trailing commas are permitted."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:74
msgid ""
"**`Block`**: Curly braces enclosing a list of statements separated by "
"semicolons and ending with an optional tail expression."
msgstr ""

#: src/references/syntax-spec.md:75
msgid ""
"**`SeqOf`**: Syntactic concatenation of multiple elements without separating "
"punctuation (e.g. `foo bar [1]` compiles to a `SeqOf` containing three "
"items)."
msgstr ""

